Standard News</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/mhairi-black-trans-debate-gender-sex-snp-westminster-b1099393.html" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br><div class="similar"><span>For more reading on this topic:</span><br>1. Source: Standard News - <a href="https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/mhairi-black-westminster-snp-holyrood-america-b1099391.html" target="_blank">Mhairi Black: Trans people should be ‘left the hell alone’ </a><br></div></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/law-society-home-office-lee-anderson-people-government-b1099290.html" target="_blank">Minister defends immigration lawyer task force as critics brand it ‘red herring’ </a></h2><div class="description"> Justice Secretary Alex Chalk said it was right to root out a ‘tiny minority’ of lawyers damaging the reputation of others. Justice Secretary said the move was necessary to tackle a 'tiny minority' of lawyers who damaged others' reputation. He added that it is right to remove lawyers who damage reputation of other lawyers.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 13:13:50 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">Standard News</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/law-society-home-office-lee-anderson-people-government-b1099290.html" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br><div class="similar"><span>For more reading on this topic:</span><br>1. Source: Standard News - <a href="https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/suella-braverman-lee-anderson-home-office-law-society-government-b1099232.html" target="_blank">Suella Braverman says task force will target ‘crooked immigration lawyers’ </a><br></div></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/bibby-stockholm-alex-chalk-law-society-suella-braverman-home-office-government-b1099255.html" target="_blank">Minister likens UK asylum system to leaky bucket after first migrants board barge </a></h2><div class="description"> The first 15 migrants have boarded the Bibby Stockholm but up to 20 others were granted a last-minute reprieve after legal challenges. Up to 20 other migrants have been granted a reprieve following legal challenges to board the ship. The Bibby is the first ship to sail from Stockholm to Stockholm.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 07:44:02 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">Standard News</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/bibby-stockholm-alex-chalk-law-society-suella-braverman-home-office-government-b1099255.html" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br><div class="similar"><span>For more reading on this topic:</span><br>1. Source: Standard News - <a href="https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/andrew-matthews-portland-dorset-english-cctv-b1099262.html" target="_blank">What will life be like for migrants on board the Bibby Stockholm barge? </a><br></div></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/aug/08/uk-electoral-commission-registers-targeted-by-hostile-hackers" target="_blank">Millions of UK voters’ data accessible in cyber-attack, says Electoral Commission</a></h2><div class="description"> The data of millions of voters was accessible to hackers in a cyber-attack by “hostile actors” discovered almost a year ago, the Electoral Commission has admitted. It was discovered in October last year and reported it to the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) and the National Crime Agency.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 13:46:11 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/aug/08/uk-electoral-commission-registers-targeted-by-hostile-hackers" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/08/fears-over-antarctic-sea-ice-as-yearly-ozone-layer-hole-forms-very-early" target="_blank">Fears over Antarctic sea ice as yearly ozone layer hole forms ‘very early’</a></h2><div class="description"> Experts say larger-than-normal hole could cause further warming of Southern Ocean and heighten damaging effects of 2022 Tonga volcano eruption. The hole in the ozone layer has begun to form early this year, prompting warnings that a larger than average hole may further warm the Southern Ocean while the level of Antarctic sea ice is at a record low.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:00:32 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/08/fears-over-antarctic-sea-ice-as-yearly-ozone-layer-hole-forms-very-early" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/08/lucy-letby-murder-trial-jury-told-reach-majority-verdict" target="_blank">Lucy Letby trial jury told it can reach majority verdict</a></h2><div class="description"> Lucy Letby is charged with murdering seven babies and attempting to murder 10 others at Chester hospital. Jury told they can now reach verdicts on which at least 10 of them agree. Panel of seven women and four men had been deliberating for 76 hours before judge told them they could now reach majority verdicts.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:31:44 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/08/lucy-letby-murder-trial-jury-told-reach-majority-verdict" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2023/aug/08/suella-braverman-immigration-lawyers-asylum-bibby-stockholm-uk-politics-live" target="_blank">Sadiq Khan accuses Lee Anderson of stoking hate with ‘back to France’ anti-migrant comment – UK politics live</a></h2><div class="description"> Foreign Office has announced fresh sanctions against Russia, which it says will limit Vladimir Putin’s access to foreign military equipment. The sanctions cover 22 individuals and businesses outside Russia “supporting Putin's illegal invasion of Ukraine,” the Foreign Office said in a news release.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:18:57 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2023/aug/08/suella-braverman-immigration-lawyers-asylum-bibby-stockholm-uk-politics-live" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/leaders-of-amazon-nations-gather-in-brazil-for-summit-on-rainforests-future" target="_blank">Leaders of Amazon nations gather in Brazil for summit on rainforest’s future</a></h2><div class="description"> Leaders of Amazon nations including Brazil, Colombia and Peru have gathered in the Brazilian city of Belém for a rare conclave about the future of the world’s largest rainforest. The environmental summit – convened by Brazil’�s leftist president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva – represents a handbrake turn in Brazilian government policy after four years of Amazon destruction.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 13:17:48 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/leaders-of-amazon-nations-gather-in-brazil-for-summit-on-rainforests-future" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/five-officers-arrested-in-marseille-over-death-of-man-during-riots" target="_blank">Five police officers arrested in Marseille over death of man in riots</a></h2><div class="description"> Mohamed Bendriss went into cardiac arrest, probably after being struck by ‘flash-ball type’ police projectile, prosecutor says. The 27-year-old man died during rioting in the French city on 1 July. Officers were among 20 members of the elite Raid (Research, assistance, intervention, dissuasion) tactical unit.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 14:50:24 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/five-officers-arrested-in-marseille-over-death-of-man-during-riots" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/08/england-to-deny-covid-and-flu-jabs-to-under-65s-amid-fears-for-nhs-this-winter" target="_blank">England to deny Covid and flu jabs to under-65s despite fears for NHS this winter</a></h2><div class="description"> Government accepts advice from JCVI which says only at-risk groups and those aged 65 and over should be offered vaccines. Millions of people under the age of 65 in England will be denied flu and Covid jabs this winter despite one of the government’s top public health officials warning that coronavirus has not “gone away”</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 13:18:24 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">health</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/08/england-to-deny-covid-and-flu-jabs-to-under-65s-amid-fears-for-nhs-this-winter" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/08/mould-found-in-lungs-of-oldham-man-who-died-in-house-with-chronic-damp-inquest-hears" target="_blank">Mould found in lungs of Oldham man who died in house with chronic damp, inquest hears</a></h2><div class="description"> Luke Brooks, 27, died from respiratory problems caused by aspergillus pneumonia after living in unheated house. His family believe mould in their privately rented end of terrace house in Oldham caused his death. Pathologist says mould was found in the lungs of a 27-year-old man.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:22:31 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/08/mould-found-in-lungs-of-oldham-man-who-died-in-house-with-chronic-damp-inquest-hears" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/thailand-king-estranged-son-surprise-return-royal-family-succession-vacharaesorn-vivacharawongse" target="_blank">Thailand king’s estranged son makes surprise return after 27 years</a></h2><div class="description"> Vacharaesorn Vivacharawongse makes what appeared to be a low-key arrival at Suvarnabhumi airport on Sunday. The estranged second son of Thailand’s king has returned to Bangkok for the first time in almost three decades.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 14:50:32 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/thailand-king-estranged-son-surprise-return-royal-family-succession-vacharaesorn-vivacharawongse" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/aug/08/ai-could-identify-passwords-by-sound-of-keys-being-pressed-study-suggests" target="_blank">AI can identify passwords by sound of keys being pressed, study suggests</a></h2><div class="description"> Researchers create system using sound recordings that can work out what is being typed with more than 90% accuracy. Experts say as video conferencing tools such as Zoom have grown in use, and devices with built-in microphones have become ubiquitous, the threat of cyber-attacks based on sounds has also risen.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 14:44:29 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">health</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/aug/08/ai-could-identify-passwords-by-sound-of-keys-being-pressed-study-suggests" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2023/aug/08/russia-ukraine-war-live-updates-moscow-missile-attack-pokrovsk-injuries-deaths" target="_blank">Russia-Ukraine war live: Kyiv claims to have foiled Russian hacking of armed forces combat system</a></h2><div class="description"> Nine people were wounded in yesterday's attack on Kruglyakivka in Kharkiv region, among them two rescuers and two policemen. In the last 24 hours, Russian troops shelled <strong>Kherson oblast 68 times. In Kherson, residential areas and a “point of invincibility” were targeted.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:14:59 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2023/aug/08/russia-ukraine-war-live-updates-moscow-missile-attack-pokrovsk-injuries-deaths" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/russian-strike-on-ukraine-city-kills-five-damaging-hotel-frequented-by-journalists" target="_blank">Russian strike on Ukraine city kills seven, damaging hotel used by journalists</a></h2><div class="description"> Two missile strikes on eastern Ukrainian city of Pokrovsk killed at least seven people and injured scores more. Hotel and pizzeria used by correspondents damaged in attack, say officials. Moscow said it had struck an ‘ordinary residential building’, publishing footage of a typical Soviet-era five-storey building.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 08:53:57 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/russian-strike-on-ukraine-city-kills-five-damaging-hotel-frequented-by-journalists" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/russia-releases-history-schoolbook-praising-ukraine-invasion" target="_blank">Russia releases history schoolbook praising Ukraine invasion</a></h2><div class="description"> Kremlin has tightened its control over the historical narrative in schools under Vladimir Putin. Trend has hugely accelerated since president launched full-scale war on Ukraine in 2022. Moscow has unveiled new history textbooks that defend Russia’s invasion of Ukraine before children return to school in September.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 10:35:36 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/russia-releases-history-schoolbook-praising-ukraine-invasion" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/ukraine-creates-database-of-art-linked-to-sanctions-hit-russians" target="_blank">Ukraine creates database of art linked to sanctions-hit Russians</a></h2><div class="description"> Ukraine’s National Agency on Corruption Prevention (NACP) has created a database of 300 pieces of art linked to sanctions. The database has been entered into a searchable database set up by the agency. It includes Leonardo da Vinci's Salvator Mundi and Andy Warhol's Four Marilyns.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 04:00:03 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/ukraine-creates-database-of-art-linked-to-sanctions-hit-russians" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/08/tiktok-how-shopping-went-social-hooked-new-generation" target="_blank">‘Where did I get my top? TikTok!’ How shopping went social – and hooked a new generation</a></h2><div class="description"> Zainab Hakim, 23, watches sellers livestream on social media site TikTok, peddling their wares in real time. With a couple of clicks, she can buy things via the app. “I probably have an addiction at this point,” she says. ‘I just get sucked in.”</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 13:00:28 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/08/tiktok-how-shopping-went-social-hooked-new-generation" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/08/suella-braverman-symposium-of-stupidity-delivers-blue-sky-thinking-on-asylum-seekers" target="_blank">Suella’s symposium of stupidity delivers blue-sky thinking on asylum seekers | John Crace</a></h2><div class="description"> Suella Braverman assembles feeblest minds in the country to find someone else to blame for government failures. It was the government’s August extravaganza: small boats week. The latest distraction from the cost of living crisis. A time to make everyone think foreigners were the reason they were broke.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:37:41 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/08/suella-braverman-symposium-of-stupidity-delivers-blue-sky-thinking-on-asylum-seekers" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/aug/08/the-death-of-the-nightclub-what-britain-will-lose-when-the-dancing-stops" target="_blank">The death of the nightclub: what Britain will lose when the dancing stops</a></h2><div class="description"> More than a third of Britain’s nightclubs have closed since June 2020. Yet they boost mental health and artistic innovation - and bring in billions for the economy. Said to have their roots in the drinking, dancing and gambling dens of mid-19th century New York.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:03:37 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/aug/08/the-death-of-the-nightclub-what-britain-will-lose-when-the-dancing-stops" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/08/dollhouses-miniatures-popularity" target="_blank">Beyond the Barbie Dream House: why mini homes are having a big moment</a></h2><div class="description"> Growing interest in dollhouses suggests people find solace and joy in tiny things – especially when real homes are so pricey. The studio apartment came with modest furnishings: a small bed, a couch, books, a TV. The original dollhouse was a 1962 folding cardboard studio apartment.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:00:25 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/08/dollhouses-miniatures-popularity" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/lauren-james-made-a-stupid-mistake-but-we-need-to-have-more-compassion-moving-the-goalposts-england-womens-world-cup" target="_blank">Lauren James made a stupid mistake – but we need to have more compassion | Suzy Wrack</a></h2><div class="description"> England forward lost composure against Nigeria but people need to take into account that players are human beings too. No one will be able to beat up James more than she will be doing to herself, so why pile on? Maybe this article shouldn’t exist either; perhaps picking over the bones of the incident feels unnecessary. Maybe there are broader points to be made about what level of criticism is appropriate in the women’s game, and the men's.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:50:17 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/lauren-james-made-a-stupid-mistake-but-we-need-to-have-more-compassion-moving-the-goalposts-england-womens-world-cup" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2023/aug/09/tv-series-like-oppenheimer-manhattan-where-to-watch-stan" target="_blank">Before Oppenheimer, there was Manhattan: this underrated drama is a must-see</a></h2><div class="description"> Despite a starry cast and strong writing, this series about the scientists living and working in Los Alamos was criminally underwatched. Manhattan is streaming on Stan.com. For more recommendations of what to stream in Australia, <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/culture/series/stream-team" click here.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:00:32 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2023/aug/09/tv-series-like-oppenheimer-manhattan-where-to-watch-stan" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/aug/08/a-smorgasbord-of-unlikability-the-authors-helping-sad-girl-lit-grow-up" target="_blank">‘A smorgasbord of unlikability’: the authors helping ‘sad girl lit’ grow up</a></h2><div class="description"> Post-Fleabag world has become obsessed with the inner turmoils of messy millennials. But isn’t it time they pulled themselves together? Meet the novelists subverting the cliches. Almost always the main character (like the author) will be middle-class, if not incredibly wealthy.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:19:43 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/aug/08/a-smorgasbord-of-unlikability-the-authors-helping-sad-girl-lit-grow-up" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/china-philippines-dispute-could-escalate-into-superpower-conflict-say-analysts" target="_blank">China-Philippines dispute could escalate into superpower conflict, say analysts</a></h2><div class="description"> Chinese coastguards used water cannon on a Philippine boat. Concerns growing as China expands and modernises its military. China shows increasing aggression in its claims over the South China Sea and Taiwan. Joint drills with Russia have also heightened concern over military coordination between Beijing and Moscow.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 10:23:42 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/china-philippines-dispute-could-escalate-into-superpower-conflict-say-analysts" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/just-ken-just-matt-hancock-barbie-tiktok-families-covid" target="_blank">Is this a star on the rise, ‘just Ken’, or just Matt Hancock? Ask the families who lost loved ones during Covid | Marina Hyde</a></h2><div class="description"> Matt Hancock mimics Ryan Gosling’s epic ballad I’m Just Ken from the Barbie movie. The former health secretary posted the video to his TikTok account. Hancock has a side hustle as well as a hobby of playing the beach. He mimics Gosling's ballad from the film.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 14:45:13 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/just-ken-just-matt-hancock-barbie-tiktok-families-covid" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/sinead-o-connor-mental-illness-mainstream-debate" target="_blank">Forget Instagram influencers, Sinéad O’Connor showed mental illness as it truly is | Hannah Jane Parkinson</a></h2><div class="description"> Sinéad O’Connor, who died last month at 56, went missing in March 2016. The Telegraph ran a live blog on the singer’s whereabouts after she had posted suicidal thoughts. I pointed out to an editor at the paper that rolling updates about a person going through a severe mental health episode, an episode that might have ended fatally, was a mistake.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 12:16:16 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/sinead-o-connor-mental-illness-mainstream-debate" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/its-almost-18-months-since-russia-invaded-ukraine-and-peace-seems-no-closer" target="_blank">It’s almost 18 months since Russia invaded Ukraine, and peace seems no closer | Rajan Menon</a></h2><div class="description"> Initiatives aimed at ending the war that Russia started by invading Ukraine have been underway for months. On 24 February – a year to the day Russia started its attack – China unveiled a proposal containing 12 principles. In June, a group of African leaders met separately with Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskiy and Russian president Vladimir Putin to present a peace plan.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 10:13:22 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/its-almost-18-months-since-russia-invaded-ukraine-and-peace-seems-no-closer" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/refugee-barges-sewage-e-coli-why-would-anyone-like-to-be-beside-the-seaside" target="_blank">Refugee barges! Sewage! E coli! Why would anyone like to be beside the seaside? | Zoe Williams</a></h2><div class="description"> Dorset is mainly in the news because of the giant refugee barge that has just taken delivery of its first residents. Even if you couldn’t see it from your beach hut – it would be charming to go to a Dorset beach when the area is.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 10:00:33 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/refugee-barges-sewage-e-coli-why-would-anyone-like-to-be-beside-the-seaside" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/halt-taliban-repression-afghan-women-girls-education" target="_blank">The world must unite now to halt the Taliban’s repression of Afghan women and girls | Gordon Brown</a></h2><div class="description"> Two years of ever-intensifying repression have not dimmed the resilience of girls and women in Afghanistan. It is time to declare it a crime against humanity, and prosecutors of the international criminal court (ICC) should open an investigation into the repression. Afghanistan's permanent representative of Afghanistan to the U.N. has called it a 'gender apartheid'</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:00:05 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/halt-taliban-repression-afghan-women-girls-education" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/remote-work-over-zoom-ordered-employees-back-to-office" target="_blank">How can you tell remote work is over? Zoom has ordered employees back to the office | Arwa Mahdawi</a></h2><div class="description"> Working from home offered the chance for a great rebalancing of family, friendship and careers. But the dream is fading fast, says Wilkie Collins. He started working from home in the corporate world and soon realised that he was extremely bad at corporate-ing. His main problem was that he liked to leave the office and have a life which was obviously a big no-no for anyone.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 14:07:44 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/remote-work-over-zoom-ordered-employees-back-to-office" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/rishi-sunak-anti-green-extremists" target="_blank">Here’s what we know about Sunak now: where the anti-green extremists lead, he will follow | Polly Toynbee</a></h2><div class="description"> Prime Minister Rishi Sunak was apparently spotted in a gym at 7am in Santa Monica, California. His family owns a £5.5m penthouse in a building with its own pet spa. 57 world triathlon athletes in Sunderland have just fallen ill in a triathlon.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 07:00:02 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/rishi-sunak-anti-green-extremists" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/britain-poor-people-leisure-victorian-workhouse" target="_blank">Britons have become so mean that many of us think poor people don’t deserve leisure time | Frances Ryan</a></h2><div class="description"> 76% of Britons believe that everyone should be able to afford utility bills. 74% think they should have the means to eat a balanced diet. A quarter of the public believe that people on out-of-work benefits shouldn’t have electricity or vitamins. Only 60% think seasonal celebrations should be attainable for all.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 05:00:00 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/britain-poor-people-leisure-victorian-workhouse" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/the-guardian-view-on-the-bibby-stockholm-a-gesture-of-self-defeating-cruelty" target="_blank">The Guardian view on the Bibby Stockholm: a gesture of self-defeating cruelty | Editorial</a></h2><div class="description"> Home Office is doomed to failure for as long as it insists on treating refugees like criminals. Asylum is granted on the basis of need, not as a conditional judgment of the route taken. Asylum seekers should not be treated as effective prisoners while their claims are being processed, says Rishi Sunak.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 17:30:46 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/the-guardian-view-on-the-bibby-stockholm-a-gesture-of-self-defeating-cruelty" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/aug/08/foreign-aid-cuts-are-a-disaster-for-women" target="_blank">Foreign aid cuts are a disaster for women | Letters</a></h2><div class="description"> Foreign aid cuts are having dire consequences for some of the world’s most vulnerable women and children, writes Prof Geeta Nargund. Plus, Lib Dem peer Malcolm Bruce on the transformational effect of aid spending. In Afghanistan, maternal mortality rates are already three times higher than the global average.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:32:34 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/aug/08/foreign-aid-cuts-are-a-disaster-for-women" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/08/left-in-limbo-by-brexit-safety-mark-chaos" target="_blank">Left in limbo by Brexit safety mark chaos | Letters</a></h2><div class="description"> Britain’s post-Brexit version of the CE mark has hampered the development of medical devices, says Roger Bayston. The enormous waste of resources due to red tape is described by Polly Toynbee as a waste of time and resources. It is not just confined to British business – it has severely affected UK research in the area of medical technology.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:32:11 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/08/left-in-limbo-by-brexit-safety-mark-chaos" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/le-sommer-fires-france-past-morocco-to-set-up-australia-quarter-final" target="_blank">Le Sommer fires France past Morocco to set up Australia quarter-final</a></h2><div class="description"> France beat the last African representatives to set up their quarter-final against the hosts at Brisbane on Saturday morning. The game promises to be one of the defining games of this tournament, a tantalising collision of Aussie guts and French guile. The match will be a gourmet feast of titanic battles: Sam Kerr against Wendie Renard, Caitlin Foord against Eve Perisset, Eugenie Le Sommer against whoever has the misfortune of trying to work out where the French are going.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 13:30:11 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/le-sommer-fires-france-past-morocco-to-set-up-australia-quarter-final" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/colombia-jamaica-womens-world-cup-last-16-match-report" target="_blank">Colombia’s Catalina Usme ends Jamaica hopes to set up England quarter-final</a></h2><div class="description"> Colombia will progress to the last eight for the first time thanks to a second-half goal from their captain, Catalina Usme. Neither team has ever made the quarter-finals before and both had helped send powerhouses home early from the group stage. Colombia's fairytale was cut short by Colombia's goal.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 10:19:09 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/colombia-jamaica-womens-world-cup-last-16-match-report" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2023/aug/08/david-squires-on-nerves-and-knockouts-at-womens-world-cup" target="_blank">David Squires on … nerves and knockouts at the Women’s World Cup</a></h2><div class="description"> England squeak through, USA bowing out and Japan having notes for next opponents Sweden. You can get a copy of this cartoon in the Guardian Print Shop. Like what David does? Consider supporting our journalism on this issue of this week's iReporter's Daily Mail.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:19:40 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2023/aug/08/david-squires-on-nerves-and-knockouts-at-womens-world-cup" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/07/england-stagger-on-at-the-world-cup-but-towards-destiny-or-the-trapdoor" target="_blank">England stagger on at the World Cup – but towards destiny or the trapdoor? | Jonathan Liew</a></h2><div class="description"> Nobody expected it to get this far a few hours ago, but then nobody expected Germany to go out in the group stage a few days ago, and nobody expected women’s football to be played in front of sell-out crowds of 50,000 a few years ago. The history of women's football is not written on the balance of probabilities.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 14:51:33 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/07/england-stagger-on-at-the-world-cup-but-towards-destiny-or-the-trapdoor" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/premier-league-2023-24-preview-no-14-manchester-united" target="_blank">Premier League 2023-24 preview No 14: Manchester United</a></h2><div class="description"> Manchester United are expected to finish third in the Premier League this season. Erik ten Hag is helping the club back on its feet and arrival of Mason Mount and André Onana is reason for optimism. But the club’s ownership needs to be resolved, says The Guardian.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:00:25 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/premier-league-2023-24-preview-no-14-manchester-united" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/wolves-gary-oneil-manager-julen-lopetegui" target="_blank">Wolves line up Gary O’Neil as manager with Julen Lopetegui poised for exit</a></h2><div class="description"> Julen Lopetegui's future in extreme doubt with future in doubt. Gary O’Neil poised to take over days before the start of the season. Wolves are concerned his frustrations could damage dressing-room morale. O'Neil out of work after sacking by Bournemouth in June.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:36:13 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/wolves-gary-oneil-manager-julen-lopetegui" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/08/england-world-cup-squad-steve-borthwick-breakdown-rugby-union" target="_blank">The Breakdown | Borthwick’s World Cup squad short on fizz and leaning on England’s past</a></h2><div class="description"> England's 33-man Rugby World Cup party for France is certainly not one to encourage much champagne-fuelled excitement among connoisseurs of expansive, enterprising rugby. England appear primarily intent on hoofing it high, chasing hard, relying on their set piece and kicking their goals.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:22:54 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/08/england-world-cup-squad-steve-borthwick-breakdown-rugby-union" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/people-were-telling-us-to-go-home-relegation-and-revival-at-burnley" target="_blank">‘People were telling us to go home’: relegation and revival at Burnley</a></h2><div class="description"> Clarets’ chairman Alan Pace reveals the abuse he received as Vincent Kompany looks to keep building. Pace insists he was reluctant to let the cameras in, and uncomfortable in front of them, but he and his fellow board members feature heavily in a four-parter that covers the sacking of Sean Dyche, relegation from the Premier League, appointment and Burnley's Championship triumph.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:00:05 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/people-were-telling-us-to-go-home-relegation-and-revival-at-burnley" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/man-dies-after-violent-clashes-between-aek-athens-and-dinamo-zagreb-fans" target="_blank">Man dies after violent clashes between AEK Athens and Dinamo Zagreb fans</a></h2><div class="description"> 29-year-old stabbed in incident on Monday night in Athens. Tuesday’s Champions League qualifier has been postponed. Police said 100 to 120 Dinamo fans had shown up late on Monday near the AEK stadium, and where AEK fans had gathered. AEK Athens and Dinamo Zagreb fans gathered outside AEK's stadium in Nea Philadelphia.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 12:02:19 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/man-dies-after-violent-clashes-between-aek-athens-and-dinamo-zagreb-fans" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/08/federico-bahamontes-first-spanish-tour-de-france-winner-dies-aged-95" target="_blank">Federico Bahamontes, first Spanish Tour de France winner, dies aged 95</a></h2><div class="description"> The first Spaniard to win the Tour de France, Federico Bahamontes, has died at the age of 95, Spanish officials say. The Spaniard was the first cyclist to complete a “career triple” by winning the “King of the Mountains” classification in all three Grand Tours. He earned the nickname “The Eagle of Toledo” after numerous victories in mountain stages.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 10:13:13 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/08/federico-bahamontes-first-spanish-tour-de-france-winner-dies-aged-95" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/07/eilinor-barker-and-neah-evans-win-world-madison-gold-for-britain" target="_blank">Elinor Barker and Neah Evans win world championship Madison gold for Britain</a></h2><div class="description"> British pair hold off Australia after crash forces late restart. Barker and Evans had to fight hard in final nine laps to hold off closest challengers Australia by just three points. Barker already a gold medallist in the women’s team pursuit at the UCI world championships in Glasgow.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 20:14:37 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/07/eilinor-barker-and-neah-evans-win-world-madison-gold-for-britain" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/08/anthony-joshua-to-face-robert-helenius-at-o2-arena-after-whyte-cancellation-boxing" target="_blank">Anthony Joshua to face Robert Helenius at O2 Arena after Whyte cancellation</a></h2><div class="description"> Anthony Joshua will fight Robert Helenius at London’s O₂ Arena on Saturday night. Finnish boxer was confirmed as Dillian Whyte's replacement after ‘adverse analytical findings’ were detected in a doping test conducted by Whyte. ‘I plan to make the most of it,’ says 39-year-old fighter.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 10:44:01 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/08/anthony-joshua-to-face-robert-helenius-at-o2-arena-after-whyte-cancellation-boxing" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/canadian-wildfire-fighters-scramble-amid-nightmare-season" target="_blank">How the climate crisis has changed wildfire fighting in Canada: ‘a chess game with Mother Nature’</a></h2><div class="description"> The Donnie Creek wildfire is the largest in British Columbia history. At more than 583,000 hectares (1.4m acres), it is larger than the Canadian province of Prince Edward Island. It could swallow nine areas the size of New York City without blinking.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 12:00:26 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/canadian-wildfire-fighters-scramble-amid-nightmare-season" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/07/in-the-absence-of-solutions-tackling-the-causes-of-antibiotic-resistance-is-key" target="_blank">In the absence of solutions, tackling the causes of antibiotic resistance is key</a></h2><div class="description"> The emergence of a possible link between air pollution and antibiotic resistance shows why action to clean up air is so badly needed. A decade ago, Britain’s top health official issued a grim warning: <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/2013/jan/23/antibiotic-resistant-diseases-apocalyptic-threat"</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 22:30:52 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">health</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/07/in-the-absence-of-solutions-tackling-the-causes-of-antibiotic-resistance-is-key" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/aug/08/climate-heating-gas-released-from-dozens-of-australian-fossil-fuel-sites-environmental-group-claims" target="_blank">Climate-heating methane released from dozens of Australian fossil fuel sites, environmental group claims</a></h2><div class="description"> Energy giants reject Australian Conservation Foundation’s infrared video investigation which claims gas leaks and venting at dozens of mines and facilities. Climate-heating methane gas is leaking or being vented from more than 100 places across 35 fossil fuel sites in Queensland and New South Wales.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:00:06 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/aug/08/climate-heating-gas-released-from-dozens-of-australian-fossil-fuel-sites-environmental-group-claims" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/drastic-action-needed-to-limit-worsening-extreme-events-in-antarctica-scientists-warn" target="_blank">‘Virtually certain’ extreme Antarctic events will get worse without drastic action, scientists warn</a></h2><div class="description"> Record low sea ice levels, the collapse of ice shelves, and surface temperatures 38.5C above average cited as concerns in new review. It is “virtually certain” that future extreme events in <a href="https://://://www.gutools.co.uk/world/antarctica">Antarctica will be worse than the extrao.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 04:31:08 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/drastic-action-needed-to-limit-worsening-extreme-events-in-antarctica-scientists-warn" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/08/west-midlands-mayor-calls-for-crooked-house-pub-to-be-rebuilt-brick-by-brick" target="_blank">West Midlands mayor calls for Crooked House pub to be rebuilt ‘brick by brick’</a></h2><div class="description"> Andy Street has called for the Crooked House pub to be ‘rebuilt brick by brick’ after it was demolished following a huge fire over the weekend. The building, known as the Britain’s ‘wonkiest pub’ and dating back to 1765, was gutted by a fire on Saturday night.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 08:19:19 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/08/west-midlands-mayor-calls-for-crooked-house-pub-to-be-rebuilt-brick-by-brick" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/08/sexually-assaulted-mp-labour-chris-bryant" target="_blank">I have been sexually assaulted by five MPs, says Labour’s Chris Bryant</a></h2><div class="description"> Chris Bryant, the Labour MP for Rhondda, has made the revelation in his new book, Code of Conduct, Why We Need to Fix Parliament – and How to Do it. He said he has been sexually assaulted by fellow MPs on several occasions during his time in parliament.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:02:25 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/08/sexually-assaulted-mp-labour-chris-bryant" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/08/man-arrested-after-stabbing-near-british-museum-in-london" target="_blank">Man arrested after stabbing near British Museum in London</a></h2><div class="description"> Man held on suspicion of causing GBH after incident that forced evacuation and temporary closure of attraction. Scotland Yard said another man was being treated for a stab wound to his arm. Incident happened at the junction of Great Russell Street and Museum Street at about 10am on Tuesday.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 12:11:42 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/08/man-arrested-after-stabbing-near-british-museum-in-london" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2023/aug/08/strictly-contestant-amanda-abbington-denies-being-transphobic" target="_blank">Strictly contestant Amanda Abbington denies being transphobic</a></h2><div class="description"> Sherlock actor apologises for ‘stupid’ and ‘ill-informed’ past comments after social media storm. Abbington, best known for TV shows including Sherlock and Mr Selfridge, was the first star to be announced for the BBC celebrity dancing show last week.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 10:54:20 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2023/aug/08/strictly-contestant-amanda-abbington-denies-being-transphobic" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/08/ministers-accused-of-lawyer-bashing-to-distract-from-asylum-policy-failures" target="_blank">Ministers accused of ‘lawyer-bashing’ to distract from asylum policy failures</a></h2><div class="description"> Law Society says crackdown on lawyers who act improperly is distraction from UK’s failure to clear asylum claim backlog. Justice secretary has said he would be comfortable with severe punishment for immigration lawyers who engage in malpractice after the government said they could face life in jail under the terms of the Illegal Migration Act.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 08:25:40 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/08/ministers-accused-of-lawyer-bashing-to-distract-from-asylum-policy-failures" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/08/cornish-lithium-secures-536m-to-open-first-mine-for-the-metal-in-britain" target="_blank">Cornish Lithium secures £53.6m to open first mine for the metal in Britain</a></h2><div class="description"> UK Infrastructure Bank leads funding of project to extract compounds used for electric vehicle batteries. ‘The part of Cornwall nobody ever sees’: the hi-tech future for lithium and tin mining.’s first lithium mine in Cornwall has secured $67m (£53.6m) of investment.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 12:19:47 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/08/cornish-lithium-secures-536m-to-open-first-mine-for-the-metal-in-britain" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/08/workers-at-uk-munitions-plant-that-supplies-ukraine-to-strike-over-pay" target="_blank">Workers at UK munitions plant that supplies Ukraine to strike over pay</a></h2><div class="description"> Nearly 50 GMB members to stop work at Ayrshire site that assembles Storm Shadow and Brimstone missiles. Workers allege they have been significantly short-changed by a pay and bonuses deal given to rocket-assembly staff at the plant at Beith, in ayrshire.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 14:15:30 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/08/workers-at-uk-munitions-plant-that-supplies-ukraine-to-strike-over-pay" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/07/air-pollution-linked-rise-antibiotic-resistance-imperils-human-health" target="_blank">Air pollution linked to rise in antibiotic resistance that imperils human health</a></h2><div class="description"> Air pollution is helping to drive a rise in antibiotic resistance that poses a significant threat to human health worldwide, a global study suggests. The analysis, using data from more than 100 countries spanning nearly two decades, indicates that increased air pollution is linked with rising antibiotic resistance across every country and continent.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 22:30:52 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">health</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/07/air-pollution-linked-rise-antibiotic-resistance-imperils-human-health" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/08/palantir-lobbied-uk-disabilities-minister-software-benefits-fraud" target="_blank">Palantir lobbied UK disabilities minister to use software to tackle benefits fraud</a></h2><div class="description"> US data firm wanted to brief Tom Pursglove on how its technology could help recover ‘large amounts’ of fraud. Palantir wrote to the UK disabilities minister to brief him on technology it had recently deployed elsewhere. The company promised that it had the potential for the Department for Work and Pensions to rapidly “recover large amounts of fraud”</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 05:00:00 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/08/palantir-lobbied-uk-disabilities-minister-software-benefits-fraud" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/education/2023/aug/08/scottish-exams-pass-rate-falls-for-second-successive-year" target="_blank">Scottish exams pass rate falls for second successive year</a></h2><div class="description"> More than 144,000 school students received their National, Higher and Advanced Higher exam grades on Tuesday. Pass rates for Highers fell from 78.9% last year to 77.1% in Scotland. Grading system became stricter after the Covid pandemic, with pass rates falling for second successive year.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 12:20:47 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/education/2023/aug/08/scottish-exams-pass-rate-falls-for-second-successive-year" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/us-and-eu-leaders-urged-to-change-tack-on-kosovo-serbia-tensions" target="_blank">US and EU leaders urged to change tack on Kosovo-Serbia tensions</a></h2><div class="description"> Politicians including chairs of US and UK foreign affairs committees criticise ‘lack of pressure placed on Serbia’ They have written to US and EU leaders to urge them to reconsider their approach to easing tensions between Kosovo and Serbia. They say the ‘EU-facilitated dialogue has yet to yield positive results’</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:58:28 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/us-and-eu-leaders-urged-to-change-tack-on-kosovo-serbia-tensions" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/aug/08/thousands-gather-funeral-sinead-oconnor-ireland" target="_blank">‘She blazed a trail’: thousands gather for funeral of Sinéad O’Connor in Ireland</a></h2><div class="description"> Thousands pack seafront in Bray, County Wicklow, to bid farewell to singer and celebrate her life. By midday on Tuesday thousands were lining the seafront to greet the funeral cortege. The Irish singer had called home, and died at the age of 56.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 12:42:35 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/aug/08/thousands-gather-funeral-sinead-oconnor-ireland" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2023/aug/08/china-trade-exports-imports-slump-recovery-falters-ftse-stock-markets-inflation-business-live" target="_blank">Italy hits banks with windfall tax, sending shares sliding; China’s trade slumps – business live</a></h2><div class="description"> Italy approves 40% windfall tax on banks for 2023 as profits soar. Intesa and Sanpaolo's shares have tumbled almost 8%, while UniCredit’s are down over 6%. UK retailers forced to slash prices after July washout and interest rate rise.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:26:58 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2023/aug/08/china-trade-exports-imports-slump-recovery-falters-ftse-stock-markets-inflation-business-live" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/09/recovery-of-great-barrier-reef-stalls-as-scientists-point-to-bleaching-disease-and-starfish-attacks" target="_blank">Recovery of Great Barrier Reef stalls as scientists point to bleaching, disease and starfish attacks</a></h2><div class="description"> Experts say an El Niño climate pattern could take hold this summer, raising the risk of another mass bleaching event further. A recovery in the number of corals growing on the Great Barrier Reef over recent years has paused, with government scientists blaming bleaching, disease and attacks by starfish.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:00:30 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/09/recovery-of-great-barrier-reef-stalls-as-scientists-point-to-bleaching-disease-and-starfish-attacks" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/aug/08/uganda-president-closure-un-human-rights-office" target="_blank">Uganda’s president under attack over closure of UN human rights office</a></h2><div class="description"> President Yoweri Museveni has come under attack from campaigners and activists for forcing the closure of the UN human rights office in Uganda. Head office in the capital, Kampala, closed at the weekend. Two field offices, in Gulu and Moroto, had already ceased operating over the summer.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 12:38:44 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/aug/08/uganda-president-closure-un-human-rights-office" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/money/2023/aug/08/flexible-workspace-provider-iwg-reports-record-revenues" target="_blank">Flexible workspace provider IWG reports record revenues</a></h2><div class="description"> Flexible workspace provider IWG has reported record revenues and a doubling of profits for the first half of the year. Firm said it had signed almost as many lease agreements between January and June as in the whole of last year. The firm predicted the pandemic “big bang” in hybrid working would become permanent.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 13:45:12 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/money/2023/aug/08/flexible-workspace-provider-iwg-reports-record-revenues" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/08/gen-z-americans-white-majority-study" target="_blank">Gen Z will be last generation with white majority in US, study finds</a></h2><div class="description"> Study of updated US census data predicts that Gen Z Americans will be the last generation with a white majority. Generation Alpha will give way to a post-2012 “majority minority” Generation Alpha. Change should come around 2045, study predicts. Author says ageing ‘is not race-neutral’ but author says ageing is not race neutral.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 14:15:58 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/08/gen-z-americans-white-majority-study" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/aug/08/sales-at-vegan-burger-maker-beyond-meat-fall-by-almost-a-third" target="_blank">Sales at vegan burger maker Beyond Meat fall by almost a third</a></h2><div class="description"> US firm cuts revenue forecast as consumers opt for cheaper animal protein amid cost of living crisis. Beyond Meat has cut its annual revenue forecast in latest sign that the vegan food bubble is bursting. The firm's plant-based products include burgers that appear to bleed and imitations of sausages and meatballs.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 07:33:33 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/aug/08/sales-at-vegan-burger-maker-beyond-meat-fall-by-almost-a-third" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/firefighters-tackling-blaze-raging-in-southern-portugal-fire" target="_blank">Firefighters battle blaze raging for fourth day in southern Portugal</a></h2><div class="description"> Nearly 1,000 firefighters in Portugal have been scrambling to contain a wildfire that has raged for four days. The wildfire has scorched thousands of hectares and forced evacuation of 1,400 people. Spain's third heatwave of the summer is expected to send temperatures soaring as high as 43C.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 14:54:01 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/firefighters-tackling-blaze-raging-in-southern-portugal-fire" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/08/biden-grand-canyon-new-national-monument" target="_blank">Biden to designate 1m acres around Grand Canyon a national monument</a></h2><div class="description"> The Baaj Nwaavjo I’tah Kukveni Grand Canyon monument – home to several Native tribes – will be protected from uranium mining. The designation comes after years-long lobbying by tribal leaders and local environmentalists to block mining projects that they say would damage the Colorado River watershed.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 14:07:34 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/08/biden-grand-canyon-new-national-monument" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/08/marvel-vfx-artists-take-first-step-toward-unionisation-amid-hollywood-strikes" target="_blank">Marvel VFX artists take first step toward unionisation amid Hollywood strikes</a></h2><div class="description"> A group of on-set VFX artists employed by the studio have filed a petition with the US’s National Labor Relations Board. The International Alliance of Theatrical Stage Employees (IATSE) said a supermajority of Marvel's 50-plus VFX crew had signed authorisation cards indicating they wished to be represented by the union.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:31:33 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/08/marvel-vfx-artists-take-first-step-toward-unionisation-amid-hollywood-strikes" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/08/william-friedkin-obituary" target="_blank">William Friedkin obituary</a></h2><div class="description"> American director behind two of the great film cult classics of the 1970s: The French Connection and The Exorcist. Friedkin had come to cinema through TV and documentary, but made a vital contribution to the American new wave. He was slightly older than the 'movie brats' group credited with revolutionising US cinema in the late 1960s and early 70s.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 12:31:01 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/08/william-friedkin-obituary" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/08/guardian-readers-cinema-etiquette-bad-behavior-anecdotes" target="_blank">‘I always confront’: Guardian readers on the decline of cinema etiquette</a></h2><div class="description"> Reader walked out of a showing of Barbie at the Odeon last week due to the behaviour of other people in the cinema – they were scrolling through phones, chatting as if they were in their own front room, waving their arms in the air during the musical number and whooping every time Ryan Gosling's face appeared on screen.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 08:05:03 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/08/guardian-readers-cinema-etiquette-bad-behavior-anecdotes" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/aug/08/the-well-of-saint-nobody-by-neil-jordan-review-the-film-makers-new-novel-is-full-of-marvels" target="_blank">The Well of Saint Nobody by Neil Jordan review – the film-maker’s new novel is full of marvels</a></h2><div class="description"> The Well of Saint Nobody is Neil Jordan’s beautiful and deceptively simple tale of love, rejuvenation and losses restored. It is a reminder of Jordan's gifts as a writer, says the author. West Cork is a place apart, but something of the old magic survives. It pervades the story of a once successful concert pianist who finds love and rejuvenation before mystical forces intervene.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 06:00:01 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/aug/08/the-well-of-saint-nobody-by-neil-jordan-review-the-film-makers-new-novel-is-full-of-marvels" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/08/king-coal-documentary-appalachia" target="_blank">‘It’s not just Appalachia’s problem’: imagining a future without coal</a></h2><div class="description"> The film-maker Elaine McMillion Sheldon grew up roving around West Virginia. Her father worked for a mining company, and the family moved to seven coal fields in 12 years for his job. “Everybody in my community worked in the coal mines,” she said. “If you were going to stay there and work, if you weren’t a doctor or a lawyer, that’s what you did.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:10:30 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/08/king-coal-documentary-appalachia" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2023/aug/08/an-interrogation-review-chilling-live-stream-summerhall-edinburgh-festival" target="_blank">An Interrogation review – chilling investigation unmasks our prejudices</a></h2><div class="description"> Jamie Armitage's mini police procedural uses live-stream cameras to manipulate the audience’s point of view in its cat-and-mouse crime story. It is a head-to-head between Ruth Palmer (Bethan Cullinane) and suspect Cameron Andrews (Jamie Ballard)</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:29:12 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2023/aug/08/an-interrogation-review-chilling-live-stream-summerhall-edinburgh-festival" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/discover-the-best-of-the-caribbean/2023/jun/07/nightlife-loveseats-and-beautiful-beaches-why-the-caribbean-makes-for-the-perfect-romantic-holiday" target="_blank">Nightlife, loveseats and beautiful beaches: why the Caribbean makes for the perfect romantic holiday</a></h2><div class="description"> The Caribbean is an unbeatable destination for a romantic getaway. From Jamaica to the hidden gem that is Curaçao, there’s something to suit every couple, whether on honeymoon, celebrating an anniversary, or just escaping. Each of the many islands has its own unique history and vibe – and they all have plenty to offer.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 07 Jun 2023 10:37:40 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/discover-the-best-of-the-caribbean/2023/jun/07/nightlife-loveseats-and-beautiful-beaches-why-the-caribbean-makes-for-the-perfect-romantic-holiday" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/discover-the-best-of-the-caribbean/2023/jun/07/waterfalls-history-and-the-worlds-first-underwater-sculpture-park-seven-exciting-things-to-do-in-the-caribbean" target="_blank">Waterfalls, history and the world’s first underwater sculpture park: seven exciting things to do in the Caribbean</a></h2><div class="description"> The islands of the Caribbean are like nowhere else on Earth. From cocktails to coral reefs, they offer something for all tastes and tempos. Enjoy sunset cocktails on the white sand beaches of Barbados or Jamaica. Enjoy a classic mojito or piña colada at the heart of the reggae-infused warmth of Jamaica.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 07 Jun 2023 10:36:40 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/discover-the-best-of-the-caribbean/2023/jun/07/waterfalls-history-and-the-worlds-first-underwater-sculpture-park-seven-exciting-things-to-do-in-the-caribbean" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/discover-the-best-of-the-caribbean/2023/jun/07/from-snorkelling-to-surfing-nine-must-try-caribbean-beach-and-water-activities" target="_blank">From snorkelling to surfing: nine must-try Caribbean beach and water activities</a></h2><div class="description"> The Caribbean offers a huge variety of tempting activities from snorkelling to scuba diving. Windsurfing and waterskiing is a must-try activity for everyone. Scuba diving is a great way to explore the most beautiful coral reefs imaginable. The Caribbean is home to some of the world’s most beautiful, vivid coral reefs.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 07 Jun 2023 10:38:48 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/discover-the-best-of-the-caribbean/2023/jun/07/from-snorkelling-to-surfing-nine-must-try-caribbean-beach-and-water-activities" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/discover-the-best-of-the-caribbean/gallery/2023/jun/07/from-pig-beach-to-dunns-river-falls-10-must-visit-caribbean-destinations-in-pictures" target="_blank">From Pig Beach to Dunn’s River Falls: 10 must-visit Caribbean destinations – in pictures</a></h2><div class="description"> The Caribbean is home to the world’s best beaches, pretty towns, waterfalls and national parks. Visit the Caribbean in all its glory. Visit the world's best beaches and waterfalls in the Caribbean. Visit CNN.com/Travel next Friday for more Caribbean travel stories.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 07 Jun 2023 10:35:34 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/discover-the-best-of-the-caribbean/gallery/2023/jun/07/from-pig-beach-to-dunns-river-falls-10-must-visit-caribbean-destinations-in-pictures" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/08/the-isometric-secret-15-ways-to-get-much-fitter-without-moving-a-muscle" target="_blank">The isometric secret: 15 ways to get much fitter – without moving a muscle</a></h2><div class="description"> The plank and wall sit are the best exercises to reduce your blood pressure. Here is how to do them – and some other great poses – whatever your current fitness level. Isometrics were most likely to reduce blood pressure, with full-body movements such as the wall squat showing bigger benefits than moves such  moves such as wall squat.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:00:04 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/08/the-isometric-secret-15-ways-to-get-much-fitter-without-moving-a-muscle" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/food/2023/aug/08/nigel-slater-midweek-breakfast-grilled-greengages-bircher-muesli-and-maple-syrup" target="_blank">Nigel Slater’s recipe for grilled greengages, bircher muesli and maple syrup</a></h2><div class="description"> An unusual, luxurious take on a healthy fruity breakfast classic. Weigh 250g of greengages and cut each fruit in half. Sugar the fruit generously with 2 tbsp of caster sugar. Cook for 7-10 minutes until soft and lightly caramelised until soft.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:01:25 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/food/2023/aug/08/nigel-slater-midweek-breakfast-grilled-greengages-bircher-muesli-and-maple-syrup" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/08/my-partners-vagina-has-atrophied-and-she-is-struggling-to-reach-climax" target="_blank">My partner’s vagina has atrophied – and she is struggling to reach climax</a></h2><div class="description"> Following a hysterectomy, penetration is uncomfortable for her after 15 years of having sex. She has been unable to climax through penetration, which is new for her. Are there ways I can help? Send your story to iReport.com/help@dailymailonline.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:13:42 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/08/my-partners-vagina-has-atrophied-and-she-is-struggling-to-reach-climax" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/food/2023/aug/09/easy-and-cheesy-three-savoury-bakes-for-school-lunchboxes-recipes" target="_blank">Easy and cheesy: three savoury bakes for school lunchboxes – recipes</a></h2><div class="description"> Cookbook author George Georgievski AKA School Lunchbox Dad, comes simple cheddar muffins, freezer-friendly frittata slices and a new spin on pizza. Get creative with whatever veggies you like in this recipe for your school lunchesboxed meals.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:00:32 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/food/2023/aug/09/easy-and-cheesy-three-savoury-bakes-for-school-lunchboxes-recipes" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/food/2023/aug/08/family-favourites-movie-night-snacks-to-steal-the-show-kitchen-aide-anna-berrill" target="_blank">Family favourites: movie night snacks to steal the show | Kitchen aide</a></h2><div class="description"> Chef Tom Kerridge's 'amazing chocolate popcorn bars' can be made up to a week ahead. Dark chocolate is non-neg, so are ‘perfect for impromptu movie nights with the kids inviting friends over at the last minute’ The snack bars can be kept in the fridge for a week and can easily be made in advance.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 13:00:27 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/food/2023/aug/08/family-favourites-movie-night-snacks-to-steal-the-show-kitchen-aide-anna-berrill" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2023/aug/08/snoring-slobs-and-splitting-the-bills-19-ways-to-holiday-with-friends-without-falling-out" target="_blank">Snoring, slobs and splitting the bills: 19 ways to holiday with friends – without falling out</a></h2><div class="description"> 65% of people planning to travel in the next 36 months will be doing so with friends. The sudden change from casual socialising to spending 24/7 together can be challenging. Here’s how to navigate some common sources of stress – and ensure you’re all still speaking to each other when you get home.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 04:00:03 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2023/aug/08/snoring-slobs-and-splitting-the-bills-19-ways-to-holiday-with-friends-without-falling-out" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2023/jul/13/why-barcelonas-beaches-are-disappearing-video" target="_blank">Why Barcelona’s beaches are disappearing – video</a></h2><div class="description"> In 2010, Barcelona’s nine city beaches were topped up with 700,000 cubic metres of sand. Since then 70% of that sand has disappeared. In the past 20 years the rate of erosion along Spain's east coast has been accelerating. It is partly to do with storms and rising sea levels but there are other factors at play.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 13 Jul 2023 08:46:44 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">tech</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2023/jul/13/why-barcelonas-beaches-are-disappearing-video" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/video/2023/jun/22/what-you-need-to-know-about-the-extreme-heatwave-hitting-our-oceans-video-explainer" target="_blank">What you need to know about the 'extreme' heatwave hitting our oceans – video explainer</a></h2><div class="description"> Sea temperatures off the north-east coast of England and west of Ireland are several degrees above normal, breaking records for late spring and early summer. The Met Office said global sea surface temperatures in April and May reached an all-time high, and June is likely to follow suit. Experts said marine heatwaves have a similar impact on the environment as wildfires on land.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 22 Jun 2023 14:22:05 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/video/2023/jun/22/what-you-need-to-know-about-the-extreme-heatwave-hitting-our-oceans-video-explainer" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2023/jul/25/i-was-a-terrorist-now-i-run-a-kindergarten-video" target="_blank">I was a terrorist. Now I run a kindergarten – video</a></h2><div class="description"> Hendi Suhartono was part of a plot to detonate four book bombs and blow up a church in Indonesia. He spent seven years in prison after going through a deradicalisation process. After being released from prison, he received support to open a kindergarten. He meets a friend from his past, Pepi Fernando, and they discuss what led to his radicalisation.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 09:15:15 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2023/jul/25/i-was-a-terrorist-now-i-run-a-kindergarten-video" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/news/video/2023/jul/04/nhs-founder-would-turn-in-his-grave-as-service-faces-crisis-at-75-video" target="_blank">Inside the NHS as staff say future hangs in the balance – video</a></h2><div class="description"> The NHS was launched in 1948 by Labour MP Aneurin Bevan, inspired in part by the Tredegar Medical Aid Society in his constituency. It has since saved the lives of millions and inspired health systems around the world. Seventy-five years on, the Guardian video team was given access to NHS services in south Wales town.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 04 Jul 2023 10:19:40 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/news/video/2023/jul/04/nhs-founder-would-turn-in-his-grave-as-service-faces-crisis-at-75-video" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/video/2023/jul/19/what-is-supercharging-the-global-heat-video-explainer" target="_blank">What is supercharging the global heat? – video explainer</a></h2><div class="description"> The planet is being hit with a double whammy of global heating in 2023: on top of the rise in global temperature caused by greenhouse gas emissions is an emerging El Niño. This sporadic event is the biggest natural influence on year-to-year weather. The Guardian's environment editor, Damian Carrington, explains what El Niño is and how it affects extreme weather.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 16:48:08 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/video/2023/jul/19/what-is-supercharging-the-global-heat-video-explainer" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/education/video/2023/jul/28/how-i-survived-a-sex-ed-shitstorm-video" target="_blank">How I survived a 'sex-ed shitstorm' – video</a></h2><div class="description"> Cartoonist Fiona Katauskas's book, The Amazing True Story of How Babies are Made, had been on Kmart and Big W shelves for three years. What started as a debate over the offending picture on Facebook would explode over several days into multiple headlines. Here is her take on what happened.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 15:00:43 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/education/video/2023/jul/28/how-i-survived-a-sex-ed-shitstorm-video" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/video/2023/jul/11/kids-vs-cars-taking-back-play-space-on-british-streets-video" target="_blank">Kids v cars: the campaign to reclaim children's play space on British streets – video</a></h2><div class="description"> Families are campaigning for children to have fun outdoors again. The Guardian’s Harriet Grant travels to Bristol to meet a group that is helping to close streets to cars to reclaim the space on children's doorsteps. Playing Out aims to reclaim play space on the doorsteps of children's front door.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 11 Jul 2023 09:30:38 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/video/2023/jul/11/kids-vs-cars-taking-back-play-space-on-british-streets-video" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/education/2023/aug/08/uk-students-do-you-plan-to-live-at-home-during-university" target="_blank">UK students: do you plan to live at home during university?</a></h2><div class="description"> More than 90% of higher education students are worried about the rising cost of living. We want to speak to students who are living at home this year amid rising costs. Are you planning to commute in? Or are you going to live on campus? Are there other ways you plan on saving costs?</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 12:33:25 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/education/2023/aug/08/uk-students-do-you-plan-to-live-at-home-during-university" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/money/2023/aug/08/uk-workers-are-you-struggling-to-get-the-hours-youd-like-to-work" target="_blank">UK workers: are you struggling to get the hours you’d like to work?</a></h2><div class="description"> We want to hear from ‘underemployed’ UK workers who are not getting as much work as they’d like. Whether you’ve had trouble finding full time work, have had shifts cancelled regularly or have had your hours reduced permanently by your employer since you signed up for the job.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 13:27:23 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/money/2023/aug/08/uk-workers-are-you-struggling-to-get-the-hours-youd-like-to-work" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/03/tell-us-how-have-you-been-impcted-by-extreme-weather-in-britain" target="_blank">Tell us: how have you been impacted by extreme weather in the UK?</a></h2><div class="description"> We want to hear how people have been affected by heatwaves, storms and flooding in the UK in the last few years. Around the world, 2023 has been a year of deadly extreme weather, from wildfires in Greece to deadly heatwaves in India and Canada. We ask people to share their experiences of being affected by extreme weather.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:25:53 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/03/tell-us-how-have-you-been-impcted-by-extreme-weather-in-britain" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/money/2023/aug/08/uk-graduates-share-your-experience-of-applying-for-jobs-after-university" target="_blank">UK graduates: share your experience of applying for jobs after university</a></h2><div class="description"> Recruitment and Employment Confederation and KPMG’s Report on Jobs has found that permanent job placements have declined at the quickest rate in just over three years amid a weak economic outlook and reduced confidence among UK businesses. Recent graduates and those starting their careers are finding the search for employment.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:17:37 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/money/2023/aug/08/uk-graduates-share-your-experience-of-applying-for-jobs-after-university" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/science/audio/2023/aug/08/summer-picks-should-we-ban-artificial-grass-podcast" target="_blank">Summer picks: should we ban artificial grass? – podcast</a></h2><div class="description"> Madeleine Finlay speaks to Guardian feature writer Sam Wollaston and urban ecologist Prof Rob Francis about why people go for artificial grass, its environmental impact, and whether it’s time we rid ourselves of the idea of the perfect lawn altogether. Read about the plastic lawn backlash from this episode from April 2023.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 04:00:04 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/science/audio/2023/aug/08/summer-picks-should-we-ban-artificial-grass-podcast" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/news/audio/2023/aug/08/the-legacy-of-sinead-oconnor-podcast" target="_blank">The legacy of Sinéad O’Connor – podcast</a></h2><div class="description"> Film-maker Kathryn Ferguson and journalist Simon Hattenstone share their memories of Sinéad O'Connor and reflect on her impact on music and society. Ferguson directed Nothing Compares, a 2022 documentary about the singer's life. She explains why O’Connor spoke out about abuse in the early 1990s when it was still taboo to do so.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 02:00:00 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/news/audio/2023/aug/08/the-legacy-of-sinead-oconnor-podcast" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/audio/2023/aug/07/world-cup-england-nigeria-australia-denmark" target="_blank">Women’s Football Weekly: Lionesses find a way to win after James red card</a></h2><div class="description"> England beat Nigeria on penalties to reach the quarter-finals of the Women's World Cup. Lauren James will miss out after being sent off in the last 16 of the tournament. Andi Hickman, Faye Carruthers and Suzanne Wrack discuss the last three days of last-16 action.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 20:01:52 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/audio/2023/aug/07/world-cup-england-nigeria-australia-denmark" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/audio/2023/aug/07/efl-arsenal-shake-city-hoodoo-football-weekly-podcast" target="_blank">EFL back with a bang and Arsenal shake City hoodoo - Football Weekly podcast</a></h2><div class="description"> Football Weekly is a weekly football podcast from the Guardian. This week's episode is hosted by Max Rushden, Ben Fisher, George Elek, Sanny Rudravajhala and Sanny Rudra. Listen to the latest episode of our weekly podcast, Football Weekly, on BBC One and Sky Sports.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 12:17:18 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/audio/2023/aug/07/efl-arsenal-shake-city-hoodoo-football-weekly-podcast" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/news/audio/2023/aug/07/how-hip-hop-gave-voice-to-a-generation-of-egyptians-hungry-for-change-podcast" target="_blank">How hip-hop gave voice to a generation of Egyptians hungry for change – podcast</a></h2><div class="description"> Music was vital to the early days of the Tahrir Square protests. The country is taking another authoritarian turn, that spirit of dissent cannot be extinguished, says The Guardian. Hip-hop gave voice to a generation of young Egyptians hungry for change, says the podcast podcast.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 04:00:29 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/news/audio/2023/aug/07/how-hip-hop-gave-voice-to-a-generation-of-egyptians-hungry-for-change-podcast" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/news/audio/2023/aug/07/how-can-we-escape-burnout-podcast" target="_blank">How can we escape burnout? | Podcast</a></h2><div class="description"> Burnout is a serious issue in workplaces across the UK. What can we do to change our working culture in order to prevent it? Read the latest episode of our podcast How Can We Escape Burnout? Please email us at www.mailonline.co.uk.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 02:00:27 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/news/audio/2023/aug/07/how-can-we-escape-burnout-podcast" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/08/krystsina-tsimanouskaya-athletics-career-poland-belarus-interview" target="_blank">Krystsina Tsimanouskaya: ‘I’m sure my career would be over if I was in Belarus now’</a></h2><div class="description"> Krystsina Tsimanouskaya has built a new life in Warsaw and won the right to run for Poland at this month’s world championships. The sprinter was ejected from the Belarus team at the Tokyo Olympics and fearing for her freedom if she returned home, sought refuge in Poland.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:20:19 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/08/krystsina-tsimanouskaya-athletics-career-poland-belarus-interview" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/08/new-orleans-archbishop-gregory-aymond-protected-alleged-abusers" target="_blank">‘My prayerful support’: how the New Orleans archbishop hid ‘credibly accused’ abusers</a></h2><div class="description"> Memo reveals Gregory Aymond disregarded recommendations from board advisers to publicly label certain accused clerics as credibly suspected molesters. Board of advisers was set up to help determine the credibility of sexual abuse allegations made against clerics under his command. But, multiple times, he has demonstrated his comfort with disregarding recommendations from those advisers.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 10:00:32 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/08/new-orleans-archbishop-gregory-aymond-protected-alleged-abusers" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/aug/08/techscape-elon-musk-x-twitter-lawsuit-ccdh-hate-speech" target="_blank">TechScape: Why Elon Musk is taking trying to mute anti-hate-speech group</a></h2><div class="description"> Twitter alleges that the Center for Countering Digital Hate drove away advertisers – but CCDH and legal experts say otherwise. The social media company’s lawsuit against an anti-hate speech group is a key reason why Elon Musk bought Twitter for $44bn last year.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 10:52:39 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">tech</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/aug/08/techscape-elon-musk-x-twitter-lawsuit-ccdh-hate-speech" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/ruzzki-not-welcome-the-russian-exiles-getting-a-hostile-reception-in-georgia" target="_blank">‘Ruzzki not welcome’: the Russian exiles getting a hostile reception in Georgia</a></h2><div class="description"> Thousands of Russians fled to Tbilisi after the invasion of Ukraine. But the graffiti that has sprung up across the city suggests not everyone is pleased to see them. “I went from a place I didn’t feel at home to a place that is not welcoming me” says Dima Belysh.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 04:00:03 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/ruzzki-not-welcome-the-russian-exiles-getting-a-hostile-reception-in-georgia" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/aug/09/early-pregnancy-loss-coalition-miscarriage-support-care" target="_blank">Unrecognised and underestimated: the fight to get Australian women proper care after miscarriages</a></h2><div class="description"> Doctors, midwives, researchers and support organisations have teamed up to change the paradigm on the 'stigma' of miscarriage. Jade Bilardi was seven weeks into her first pregnancy when she miscarried. She was already thinking ahead to when she’d take maternity leave, imagining being a mother by Mother’s Day.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:00:32 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/aug/09/early-pregnancy-loss-coalition-miscarriage-support-care" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/aug/08/explainer-whats-behind-the-niger-coup" target="_blank">Explainer: What’s behind the Niger coup?</a></h2><div class="description"> Russia's support in Niger is limited to so-called pan-Africanist or alter-globalisation circles, mainly through social media networks. Occasionally, however, street demonstrations calling for the withdrawal of the French army from Niger are made by civil society or trade unions. M62, a civil society umbrella organisation set up in 2022, is one of the leading movements surfing a wave of anti-French sentiment.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 05:00:01 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/aug/08/explainer-whats-behind-the-niger-coup" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global/2022/sep/20/sign-up-for-the-fashion-statement-newsletter-our-free-fashion-email" target="_blank">Sign up for the Fashion Statement newsletter: our free fashion email</a></h2><div class="description"> Style, with substance: what’s really trending this week, a roundup of the best fashion journalism and your wardrobe dilemmas solved, delivered straight to your inbox every Thursday. We’ve got something for you whether you love film, football, fashion or food.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 20 Sep 2022 11:06:20 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global/2022/sep/20/sign-up-for-the-fashion-statement-newsletter-our-free-fashion-email" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/food/2019/jul/09/sign-up-for-word-of-mouth-the-best-of-guardian-food-every-week" target="_blank">Sign up for Word of Mouth: the best of Guardian Food every week</a></h2><div class="description"> A weekly email bringing you our best food writing, the latest recipes, seasonal eating ideas and must-read restaurant reviews. Sign up below to start receiving the best of our culinary journalism in one mouth-watering weekly email. We’ll send you latest recipes from Yotam Ottolenghi, Nigel Slater, Meera Sodha and all our star cooks.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 09 Jul 2019 08:19:21 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">health</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/food/2019/jul/09/sign-up-for-word-of-mouth-the-best-of-guardian-food-every-week" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/news/gallery/2023/aug/08/portugal-wildfires-kittens-tuesday-best-photos" target="_blank">Portugal wildfires and tree-dwelling kittens: Tuesday’s best photos</a></h2><div class="description"> The Guardian's picture editors select photo highlights from around the world. Portugal's wildfires are the focus of this week's best photos. Portugal has been hit hard by wildfires in the past year and blamed for some of the country's worst fires in recent years. Click here for more from The Guardian.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:02:26 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/news/gallery/2023/aug/08/portugal-wildfires-kittens-tuesday-best-photos" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/gallery/2023/aug/08/the-women-calling-for-reform-of-venezuelas-severe-anti-abortion-laws-in-pictures" target="_blank">The women calling for reform of Venezuela’s severe anti-abortion laws – in pictures</a></h2><div class="description"> Despite demands for change, the government shows no sign of reforming the 1926 law. Only in 2000 was it amended to allow for abortions to save the life of the pregnant woman. Venezuelans have been turning to online sellers of abortion pills or paying for costly and illegal procedures in a doctor's office.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 07:00:03 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/gallery/2023/aug/08/the-women-calling-for-reform-of-venezuelas-severe-anti-abortion-laws-in-pictures" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2023/aug/08/difference-is-beautiful-pregnant-trans-men-go-for-a-swim-in-pictures" target="_blank">‘Difference is beautiful’: pregnant trans men go for a swim – in pictures</a></h2><div class="description"> The Seahorse Parents is a photography and film project in which four soon-to-be parents share their personal stories of what carrying future children as transgender men has been like. The project was set up by four men who are expecting to have children with gender-specific genital mutilation.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 06:00:02 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2023/aug/08/difference-is-beautiful-pregnant-trans-men-go-for-a-swim-in-pictures" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2023/aug/08/2023-nature-infocus-photography-awards-winners-in-pictures" target="_blank">2023 Nature inFocus photography awards winners – in pictures</a></h2><div class="description"> The results of the Nature inFocus photography awards were announced at a festival held at Jayamahal Palace in Bengaluru, India, on Monday 31 July. The awards honour photographers documenting unique natural history moments and critical conservation issues, and generate an impressive catalogue of imaginative and artistic images every year.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 05:00:01 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2023/aug/08/2023-nature-infocus-photography-awards-winners-in-pictures" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/gallery/2023/aug/07/a-ceasefire-in-tigray-but-in-the-displaced-peoples-camps-the-suffering-goes-on-in-pictures" target="_blank">A ceasefire in Tigray, but in the displaced peoples’ camps, the suffering goes on – in pictures</a></h2><div class="description"> About 1.8 million people were displaced because of fighting in the northern Ethiopian region. Despite an end to fighting, many people are still struggling to get enough food to survive. Ximena Borrazás and Edgar Gutierrez got rare access to the camps where many people still struggle for food.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 06:00:32 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/gallery/2023/aug/07/a-ceasefire-in-tigray-but-in-the-displaced-peoples-camps-the-suffering-goes-on-in-pictures" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/met-police-assistant-commissioners-pippa-mills-matt-twist-b1099421.html" target="_blank">Met Police appoints Assistant Commissioners to help run Scotland Yard</a></h2><div class="description"> Two former Met Police constables have been appointed as Assistant Commissioners to help run Scotland Yard. Scotland Yard has been described as 'Scotland Yard's most successful force in the world' Scotland Yard was founded by the Metropolitan Metropolitan Police in 1966. The Metropolitan Police force has been in the news of the appointment of two former constables as Assistant Commissioner.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:39:54 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">Standard News</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/met-police-assistant-commissioners-pippa-mills-matt-twist-b1099421.html" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/police-gypsy-secretary-of-state-wales-conservative-b1099426.html" target="_blank">Police will take no further action regarding MP’s leaflet on Traveller sites</a></h2><div class="description"> Wales Secretary David TC Davies had defended the leaflet. Wales Secretary had defended it in a bid to protect the public from harm. Wales Minister said the letter was 'a good example of a good example' Wales Secretary said he had 'toughened up' the letter.</div><br><span 